page.text: Roach briefly explained the study in detail to the Commission members, discussing the
primary issues related to congested parking and ingress and egress issues at the school
drive approaches off of Hagadorn Road and Burcham Drive. With the addition of sixth
grade students to the Middle School this year, most concerns are expected to be magnified.

text.i: DISCUSSION OF MACDONALD MIDDLE SCHOOL TRAFFIC IMPACT STUDY

page.text: Level of service operations were also included in the study for both drives to the school and
the Hagadorn/Burcham intersection which is operated by a traffic signal. The primary
concern of the school is the westbound turning movement onto southbound Hagadorn,
which currently has a very poor level of service. Busses and parents both currently use the
drive approach off Hagadorn which has caused delays in busses getting to the school before
students are released for the day. While parents also use the drive off Burcham but often
park near or on Burcham to pick up their children causing congestions issues on the
roadway. Current traffic control devices in place at these drives are currently not followed
The vehicle delays experienced on the driveway to Hagadorn is due to a combination of
parent traffic and lack of gaps on Hagadorn which impacts left turning movements exiting
the drive. Sight restriction is also an issue as busses currently using this drive often block
the view of parents looking to exit the drive.
Traffic Engineering Associates, the consultant who completed the study, suggested the
Installing a paved pedestrian sidewalk from Hagadorn to the building to allow for
safer passage for students who walk to school or are dropped off. This allows
pedestrians to remain outside the drive and away from oncoming traffic.
Painting the curb line of the drive off Burcham yellow to provide a visual
indication that supports the No Stopping, Standing or Parking signs currently
Encouraging parents to pull further into the Burcham drive to better utilize the
designated drop-off area in front of the school.
Scheduling of busses for afternoon pickup should take place sooner so the busses
are parked and waiting for students in order to avoid conflicts with parent traffic
Final option if possible in the future, would be to separate bus and parent traffic by
constructing a new one-way exiting drive off of Burcham east of the school
building for the busses to use.
Hollstein commented that it is important to have a drive and sidewalk network that can
effectively handle the students getting to and from the school, especially with the addition
of the sixth grade student body.
O'Regan stated there is no mention of pedestrian/bicycle counts incorporated into the study
and feels no further action should be taken until the data is included.

page.text: The consultant identified necessary improvements to traffic control devices at specific locations to
allow for proper handling of the additional projected traffic. Lengthy delays are expected to be
encountered at the Grand River/Michigan intersection without proper adjustments made to the
green time. Another area of concern is the Grand River/Abbot intersection, where traffic would
likely stack if the proposed northbound left turn movement into the valet parking drive of proposed
building A was allowed. A gridlock situation would be encountered if permitting this movement.
The consultant concluded their Background Conditions notes by stating that in an ideal situation,
the developers would contract the Traffic Impact Study consultant to prepare one independent TIS
for the entire development (PDIG & DTN). The level of service is expected to become worse
without adjustments to surrounding traffic signals near the development site. These specific
locations are identified in the memo from DLZ. DLZ also recommends that the TIS be reviewed by

Traffic Engineering Associates, Inc. (TEA) conducted a traffic impact study for the proposed
Park District development, Park District Investment Group, LLC, in the City of East Lansing,
The new development will have two (2) buildings; Building A
will consist of a ten (10) story building with approximately 24,359 square feet of retail with
an 8,500 square foot restaurant on the first floor, a 120 room hotel on floors two (2) through
four (4), 102 apartments units on floors five (5) through ten (10), and two (2) levels of
underground parking with 283 parking spaces. Building B will be a four (4) story building
and will consist of an approximately 11,020 square foot retail on the first floor and 42
apartments on floors two (2) through four (4).
For this traffic impact study, it was understood that the proposed Park District development,
Park District Investment Group, LLC, could have minor changes in the site plan and small
additions or deletions in the proposed uses; therefore, the above project description was
based on the most up to date site plans available at the time the traffic impact study was
The proposed development is expected to be completed in the fall of 2016. It is not
anticipated that the project will be constructed in specific phases, as the development is
interconnected throughout and operates as a uniform site.
Parking is being provided onsite in Building A. Building A will have 283 parking spaces in a
two (2) level, underground parking, garage that will be valet parking only, and will have
direct access onto Albert Avenue, just west of Abbot Road. Patrons wishing to utilize valet
parking will need to use the Abbot Road drop-off driveway. Building B will not have onsite
parking and will be expected to park in the valet parking garage in Building A or on nearby
The intersections defined for this study were analyzed according to the methodologies
published in the most recent edition of the Highway Capacity Manual. The analysis
determines the “Level of Service” (LOS) of the intersections and is defined by average
vehicle delay in seconds created by a traffic control device for a given traffic movement, or
intersection approach. Level of Service is expressed in a range from “A” to “F,” with “A”
being the highest LOS and “F” representing the lowest LOS. Level of service “D” is
considered the minimum acceptable LOS in most urban areas.
TEA, Inc. used existing vehicle turning movement surveys which included traffic counts
during the morning and afternoon peak periods in September, 2012, after the MSU students
were back in school at the following locations:
• Abbot Road and Grand River Avenue (M-43)
TEA, Inc. used existing vehicle turning movement surveys which included traffic counts
during the morning and afternoon peak periods in October, 2012, at the following locations:
• Grand River Avenue (M-43) and Hillcrest Avenue
• Grand River Avenue (M-43) and Delta Street
TEA, Inc. used existing vehicle turning movement surveys which included traffic counts
during the morning and afternoon peak periods in February, 2014, at the following locations;
• Grand River Avenue (M-43) and Michigan Avenue
• Grand River Avenue (M-43) and MAC Avenue
The existing weekday AM and PM peak hour traffic volumes are 7:30 – 8:30 AM and 4:45 –
5:45 PM at the key locations, respectively.
All existing turning movements at the studied intersections operate at an acceptable level of
service (LOS D or better); except for the southbound thru-left turn movement at the
intersection of Abbot Road and Grand River Avenue. During the AM peak hour this
movement operates at a LOS F with 96.8 seconds of delay.
Population growth is the driving force behind area-wide traffic growth. According to the
most recent data from the US Census Bureau, from 2000-2010, Ingham County had an
exponential growth rate of zero point zero six percent (0.06%) per year, and the City of East
Lansing had a growth of zero point four three percent (0.43%) per year. Information
provided to TEA from the Tri-County Regional Planning Commission estimates an
approximate zero point five percent (0.5%) growth rate for the project area. As such, a one-
half percent growth rate was applied exponentially for a two (2) year time period to represent
population growth for the City of East Lansing.
One (1) new development was identified in the near vicinity of the Park District
development, Park District Investment Group, LLC, to be included as background
development. The proposed The Gateway development will be located between Grand River
Avenue (M-43) and Valley Court, and will also be located on the east and west side of Delta
The proposed site will contain a six (6) story building in which the ground floor will
consist of parking, a 2,625 square foot Biggby coffee shop with a patio and drive through
lane, a 2,202 square foot fitness center for apartment residents, and a 725 square foot leasing
office. The second level will contain a parking ramp situated on both sides of Delta Street
with the proposed building bridging over the roadway. The third through sixth floors will
contain 168 residential apartment units. There will also be a below grade parking facility on
the west side of Delta Street. Trip generation values were obtained from the Traffic
Engineering Associates, Inc. (TEA) traffic study dated January, 2014.
Under background conditions, all studied intersections overall are expected to operate at a
good level of service (LOS D or better). All movements are expected to operate at an
acceptable level of service (LOS D or better) except a few movements. The northbound left
turn movement at the intersection of Delta Street and Grand River Avenue (M-43), during
the PM peak hour, is anticipated to operate at a LOS E with 43.0 seconds of delay, an 18.7
second increase from existing conditions. The southbound left turn movement at the
intersection of Delta Street and Grand River Avenue (M-43), during the PM peak hour, is
anticipated to operate at a LOS E with 37.6 seconds of delay, a 16.6 second increase from
existing conditions. During the AM peak hour, the southbound left-thru movement at the
intersection of Abbot Road and Grand River Avenue (M-43) is anticipated to operate at a
LOS F with 97.6 seconds of delay, a 0.8 second increase from existing conditions.
The proposed Park District development trip generation rates were derived from the ITE Trip
Edition). In discussion with the City of East Lansing staff for the
completion of a traffic impact study for a previous development on this same site, the
Planning Department informed TEA that within the City of East Lansing zoning code there is
an allowable twenty-five percent (25%) reduction of trips for the retail development. These
reductions were included in the report. It is projected that the proposed Park District
development, Park District Investment Group, LLC, will generate 154 vehicle trips in the
AM peak hour, 260 vehicle trips in the PM peak hour, and 3,242 weekday trips.
All background geometrics and existing traffic control was utilized for the future conditions
except for the following; southbound Abbot Road will include one (1) exclusive right turn

Avenue will be extended to the west from Abbot Road to align with Valley Court; Evergreen
Avenue will be removed between Grand River Avenue and Valley Court; a new eastbound
exclusive left turn lane on Albert Avenue at Abbot Road that align with the westbound left
All proposed development driveway on Albert Road was modeled as two (2) lanes, with one

modeled as full access entering with a right turn exit only driveway.
Under future conditions, all studied intersections are projected to operate at an acceptable
level of service (LOS D or better). It is anticipated that all movements will operate at an
acceptable level of service, LOS D or better, except for the following movements. The
eastbound left turn movement at the intersection of Grand River Avenue (M-43) and Abbot
Road is anticipated to operate at a LOS E with 59.3 seconds of delay, a 14.3 second increase
from background conditions during the PM peak hour. The westbound thru-right movement
at the intersection of Grand River Avenue (M-43) and Abbot Road is anticipated to operate at
a LOS E with 56.4 seconds of delay, an 18.5 second increase from background conditions
during the PM peak hour. The westbound left turn movement at the intersection of Albert
Avenue and Abbot Road is anticipated to operate at a LOS F with 131.6 seconds of delay, an
86.1 second increase from background conditions during the PM peak hour. The northbound
thru movement at the intersection of Albert Avenue and Abbot Road is anticipated to operate
at a LOS E with 72.7 seconds of delay, a 47.4 second increase from background conditions
during the PM peak hour. The northbound left turn movement at the intersection of Delta
Street and Grand River Avenue (M-43) is anticipated to operate at a LOS F with 51.2
seconds of delay, an 8.2 second increase from background conditions during the PM peak
hour. The southbound left turn movement at the intersection of Delta Street and Grand River
Avenue (M-43) is anticipated to operate at a LOS F with 69.4 seconds of delay, a 31.8
second increase from background conditions during the PM peak hour.
To mitigate these delays, it is recommended that the traffic signal at Albert Street and Abbot
Road be retimed. At the intersection of Grand River Avenue (M-43) and Delta Street, a
signal warrant analysis was conducted. It was determined that the PM peak hour meets
Warrant 3, Peak Hour, for the recommendation of a traffic signal. As such, a new traffic
signal at this intersection was provided to offer signalized traffic control for Delta Street.
Under future mitigated conditions, all studied intersections are projected to operate at a good
level of service (LOS C or better). It is anticipated that all movements will operate at an
acceptable level of service, LOS D or better, except for the northbound thru movement at the
intersection of Albert Avenue and Abbot Road. During the PM peak hour, this movement is
anticipated to operate at a LOS E with 60.9 seconds of delay, a 1.8 second increase from
The findings of this study show that the traffic signal timing should be reevaluated at the
intersection of Albert Avenue and Abbot Road. Also, as shown on the site plans, Albert
Avenue should be extended to the west and realigned to connect with Valley Court.
As shown on the proposed site plan, reconstruct Abbot Road between Grand River Avenue

A review should be conducted in the future when the Park District development, Park
District Investment Group, LLC, is complete to determine if a traffic signal is warranted at
the intersection of Grand River Avenue (M-43) and Delta Street.

page.text: The critical intersections defined for this study were analyzed according to the methodologies
published in the most recent edition of the Highway Capacity Manual. The analysis
determines the “Level of Service” of the intersections and is based on factors such as the
number and types of lanes, signal timing, traffic volumes, pedestrian activity, etc. The level
of service (LOS) is defined by average vehicle delay in seconds created by a traffic control
device for a given traffic movement or intersection approach.
Levels of Service are expressed in a range from “A” to “F,” with “A” being the highest LOS
and “F” representing the lowest LOS. Level of service “D” is considered the minimum
acceptable LOS in an urban area.

software package which is approved by the Michigan Department of Transportation
(MDOT). Delay per vehicle includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped
The Level of Service analysis for existing traffic at the subject intersections during the peak
All existing turning movements at the studied intersections operate at an acceptable level of
service (LOS D or better); except for the southbound thru-left turn movement at the
intersection of Abbot Road and Grand River Avenue. During the AM peak hour this
movement operates at a LOS F with 96.8 seconds of delay.

Background traffic represents future volumes without the traffic generated by the proposed
Park District development, Park District Investment Group, LLC. The target year for
completion is 2016; therefore, a two (2) year growth rate was applied to the existing traffic
Population growth is the driving force behind area-wide traffic growth. According to the
most recent data from the US Census Bureau, from 2000-2010, Ingham County had an
exponential growth rate of zero point zero six percent (0.06%) per year, and the City of East
Lansing had a growth of zero point four three percent (0.43%) per year. Information
provided to TEA from the Tri-County Regional Planning Commission estimates an
approximate zero point five percent (0.5%) growth rate for the project area. As such, a one-
half percent growth rate was applied exponentially for a two (2) year time period to represent
population growth for the City of East Lansing. The proposed growth related background
weekday AM and PM peak hour traffic volumes are illustrated in Figure 2A.

north-south roadway and extends from Grand River Avenue (M-43) at the south end, to the

to join with Valley Court, and the south portion of Evergreen Avenue between Albert
Avenue and Grand River Avenue (M-43) will be eliminated.

Traffic distribution for the Park District development, Park District Investment Group, LLC,
was based on two key factors. First, the facility is providing valet parking in Building A with
access to the garage on Albert Avenue. This will be used primarily by hotel guests, residents
of the apartment complex and will also be available for retail customers. The motorist will
need to access the Abbot Road drop-off driveway at the building’s front entrance for the
valet service; therefore, all traffic to the site that does not utilize on-street parking, was
distributed to the Abbot Road valet driveway. The driveway was designed as full access
entering and right turn only exit.
There will be on-street parking available near Building B and at other locations nearby,
which would be expected to be utilized by the retail customers. It was estimated that all hotel
guests and residents would utilize the valet parking. Retail customers were split evenly
(50/50) between the valet service and nearby on-street parking. Retail traffic not using the
valet parking was distributed to the on-street parking along Albert Avenue and Valley Court.
Traffic was then distributed based on the surrounding future roadway patterns. Separate
distributions were determined for the residential use, the office space, and the commercial
uses as they all have different traffic patterns associated with their individual uses. Typically,
a residential facility has a traffic pattern where vehicles are exiting in the morning and
entering in the evening; therefore, the existing exiting traffic pattern on the roadway system
during the morning and the entering traffic pattern during the evening generated the
distribution for this study. The distribution for the residential generated traffic is as follows.
